items.title: Muscular dystrophy
items.note: Author, Donald L. Schotland.
items.summary: This program reviews muscular dystrophy with the aid of photographs of clinical examples and photomicrographs. Initially, general considerations regarding the disease are noted.    The pathological features and the results of laboratory procedures which indicate the presence of various types of muscular dystrophy are described. The clinical features of Duchenne muscular dystrophy, fascioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy, limb-girdle muscular dystrophy, myotonic disorders, and ocular muscular dystrophy are discussed in general and as they appear in specific cases.    Factors which aid in the differential diagnosis of muscular dystrophy from each of the following are identified: inflammatory myopathies, endocrine andmetabolic myopathies, congenital myopathies, glycogen storage disease, myositis ossificans, myasthenia gravis, and neurogenic disease.    A table summarizing the features of muscular dystrophy (and all myopathies) and neurogenic disease (muscular atrophies) are presented. Another table which summarizes the clinical features of the major forms of muscular dystrophy, namely, Duchenne, fascioscapulohumeral, limb-girdle, and myotonic is also included.
